    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Over Lunch at Sardi's</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Theater historian Max Wilk letter on May 21 article notes producer Brock Pemberton, John Golden and Jacob Wilk devised Tony awards over lunch at Sardi's in 1946 (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a theater historian, I would like to add to your history of the Tony Awards [''A Guide to Tony's Universe,'' May 21]. Yes, they were devised to honor Antoinette Perry, but the devisors were three honorable men: Brock Pemberton, the producer; John Golden, also an energetic man of the theater, and Jacob Wilk, who called his friends together at a table at Sardi's in 1946 for the purpose of creating some sort of theater awards. More than half a century later, their friendly lunchtime endeavors have certainly earned them an award for such a long run.</p>
        <p>MAX WILK  Santa Fe, N.M.</p>
      </block>
